a great time yesterday and a good time at

00:00:24.349 --> 00:00:27.689
the party last night.
[ Cheers and applause ]

00:00:27.689 --> 00:00:33.690
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: You know, it wasn't just us
that had a great time yesterday. We had over

00:00:33.690 --> 00:00:40.690
60,000 simultaneous viewers watch our show.
That's pretty staggering. Because it is a

00:00:40.750 --> 00:00:46.680
global audience, throughout the day, that
number increased, and total viewers yesterday

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:50.090
was just topping out over 600,000 people.
[ Applause ]

00:00:50.090 --> 00:00:53.250
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: And so --
[ Applause ]

00:00:53.250 --> 00:00:58.900
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: -- we can't thank you all
enough for the global enthusiasm that you've

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:03.350
expressed for the hard work that we're doing.
It's very, very gratifying.

00:01:03.350 --> 00:01:08.610
I hope all of you also enjoyed your Samsung
tablets.

00:01:08.610 --> 00:01:12.160
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: Are these great or what?

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:16.180
[ Cheers and applause ]
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: One thing you might have missed

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:22.690
was that, in addition to getting this tablet,
you also received this voucher. This voucher

00:01:22.690 --> 00:01:29.690
we will actually deliver on today at 3:30.
And what you'll get is one of these. This

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:35.610
is just absolutely amazing. It's a Verizon
Wi-Fi hot spot, provided through our partnership

00:01:35.610 --> 00:01:42.330
with Verizon and Samsung. On typical 4G areas,
you'll get up to 20 megabits per second down,

00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:46.409
ten megabits per second up. Typical areas
do not include this room.

00:01:46.409 --> 00:01:52.220
But I got about seven megabits down a few
moments ago in the room. But like we said,

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:54.630
please turn off your Wi-Fi hot spots for the
sake of the presentation.

00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:58.869
But I hope you enjoy this as well. This is
really, really great. Thank you to Verizon

00:01:58.869 --> 00:02:05.869
and Samsung for that.
[ Cheers and applause ]

00:02:05.869 --> 00:02:12.660
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: Let's turn our attention to
the keynote this morning.

00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:19.660
You know, from its very inception, this show
has always been about the most important platform

00:02:21.700 --> 00:02:27.099
of our era. It's a platform that's controlled
by none of us, so it's the only platform that

00:02:27.099 --> 00:02:33.420
truly belongs to all of us. And that is the
open Web. And the Chrome team has set the

00:02:33.420 --> 00:02:39.730
pace of moving the Web forward along the dimensions
of speed, along the dimensions of security,

00:02:39.730 --> 00:02:45.480
and along the dimensions of capability.
To hear what's next in the incredibly exciting

00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:49.920
story of Chrome, I'd like to introduce my
friend and senior vice president of Chrome,

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:56.920
Sundar Pichai.
[ Applause ]

00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:04.580
&gt;&gt;Sundar Pichai: Thank you. It's very exciting
to be here.

00:03:05.379 --> 00:03:10.550
Welcome to the Chrome keynote.
We have a lot to cover. We are here to talk

00:03:10.550 --> 00:03:17.550
about the open Web, the amazing platform it
is, the pace at which it's making progress.

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:22.290
Chrome is the way we manifest the Web to our
users. So we want to give you an update on

00:03:22.290 --> 00:03:29.290
Chrome, Chrome Web Store, and finally Chrome
OS. Lots to cover. Let's get started.

00:03:30.769 --> 00:03:36.730
Exactly a year ago, at Google I/O, we were
here on this stage. We were incredibly excited

00:03:36.730 --> 00:03:42.849
at the momentum behind Chrome. We announced
that over 70 million active users were using

00:03:42.849 --> 00:03:48.690
Chrome as their main browser. So it's been
a year since then. And we are back at I/O.

00:03:48.690 --> 00:03:55.690
So let's take a look at where we are now.
[ Cheers and applause ]

00:04:07.629 --> 00:04:10.440
&gt;&gt;Sundar Pichai: So we have more than doubled
in the last year. And we couldn't be more

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:13.470
pleased.
Many of you in this audience were some of

00:04:13.470 --> 00:04:19.409
the earliest adopters of Chrome and helped
get the word around. So thank you.

00:04:19.409 --> 00:04:23.190
If -- let's take a look at what's happened
since last I/O to now, within the last year.

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:30.190
So let's zoom in between the 70 to 160 million.
If you take a look, it's actually a bit tough

00:04:31.479 --> 00:04:37.130
to remember, but last year, we were at Chrome
4. So we had just launched the stable version

00:04:37.130 --> 00:04:42.740
of Chrome 4. And if you remember, it was available
only for Windows. We didn't have Mac and Linux

00:04:42.740 --> 00:04:47.940
versions. In fact, that's what most of the
team was working on, getting Chrome to be

00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:52.020
an equal citizen on the two other great platforms.
It was a lot of work. It consumed a lot of

00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:59.020
resources. And with Chrome 6, we brought Chrome
to the Mac and Linux stable channel.

00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:04.990
At that point, we made an important decision
as a team. We decided to switch to six-week

00:05:04.990 --> 00:05:10.440
release cycles. We wanted to make sure version
numbers shouldn't matter, that we continually

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:16.590
push features out, both to users, and more
importantly, to developers, as and when HTML5

00:05:16.590 --> 00:05:21.770
APIs became ready.
So let's take a look.

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:26.940
As you can see, in the last 12 months, we've
been releasing every six weeks. And this week,

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:33.070
we just launched Chrome 12 in beta. So we've
had our eight versions of Chrome just in the

00:05:33.070 --> 00:05:38.560
last year alone. The pace at which we are
pushing the Web platform forward is amazing.

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:43.320
There are a whole slough of APIs here. We'll
talk about them in more detail.

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:48.440
But we have focused on many other things as
well. Speed is something near and dear to

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:54.000
our heart. We have had over 20X speed and
JavaScript improvement last year alone. We

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:59.639
have pushed security really hard. Chrome has
a great sandbox. In addition, last year for

00:05:59.639 --> 00:06:05.509
the first time, we have sandbox plug-ins.
PDF is fully sandboxed, and Flash is partially

00:06:05.509 --> 00:06:10.520
sandboxed, and we are working on completing
the sandbox. So the progress has been great.

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:16.870
The good news is, we are not the only ones
pushing the platform forward. All browser

00:06:16.870 --> 00:06:23.870
vendors, modern browsers, are investing in
HTML5. So if you take a look at 2008, this

00:06:23.979 --> 00:06:29.949
was just under way. Chrome had launched. People
were beginning to add HTML5 APIs. We spoke

00:06:29.949 --> 00:06:36.949
about it in I/O. And if you forward to now,
the progress is amazing. All modern browsers

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:42.949
have these APIs implemented, so that you as
developers can rely on these APIs when you

00:06:42.949 --> 00:06:46.550
write applications and make sure you can deliver
a consistent experience.

00:06:46.550 --> 00:06:51.360
So let's take a look at some of the upcoming
APIs which we are excited about in Chrome.

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:58.360
To do that, I want to invite Ian Ellison-Taylor,
who's the director of the Web Platform team

00:06:59.430 --> 00:07:01.539
in Chrome.
[ Applause ]

00:07:01.539 --> 00:07:07.880
&gt;&gt;Ian Ellison-Taylor: It's a long way up.
Thanks, everybody.

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:13.650
What Sundar showed on an earlier slide, there's
been an amazing number of new features added

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:20.000
to the Web platform just over the last year
alone. And I think taken together, they add

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:25.430
up to an amazing new set of capabilities for
Web applications running in modern browsers.

00:07:25.430 --> 00:07:29.470
I think it's amazing the kinds of things that
you can build today.

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:36.050
Now, of course, we're not resting on our laurels
at Google, and with hundreds, literally hundreds,

00:07:36.050 --> 00:07:42.220
of other collaborators, new features are being
added all the time. It's a genuine community

00:07:42.220 --> 00:07:46.560
effort on everyone's part.
So I wanted to take a minute or two today

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:50.599
and just run you through some of those features.
And I'm going to start with I think one of

00:07:50.599 --> 00:07:55.669
my favorite features, one of the new and cool
features, and that's speech.

00:07:55.669 --> 00:08:01.639
So let me run through that here. I can give
you a quick demo.

00:08:01.639 --> 00:08:07.020
So for the purposes of the demo, I'm going
to use this application that's a fantastic

00:08:07.020 --> 00:08:10.870
application from the Web Store. It's called
Clicker. It lets you discover and view some

00:08:10.870 --> 00:08:17.870
of the best online Web video. So imagine for
a second I'm an engineer at Clicker, and I

00:08:20.560 --> 00:08:25.410
want to add speech to this.
So here's the little search panel inside Clicker.

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:30.110
And I want to add some speech support.
So there's lots of ways to do it. One of the

00:08:30.110 --> 00:08:35.729
easiest ways just to try things out is to
use the developer tools that are built into

00:08:35.729 --> 00:08:38.639
Chrome.
So I'm going to right-click on inspect element.

00:08:38.639 --> 00:08:42.539
And then this brings up the developer tools
that you can see in the bottom panel.

00:08:42.539 --> 00:08:47.819
Now, the developer tools in Chrome have come
a really long way in the last year or so.

00:08:47.819 --> 00:08:51.800
I think many of these features, I think, are
state of the art. So I very much encourage

00:08:51.800 --> 00:08:54.819
you to check out the developer tools session
a little bit later.

00:08:54.819 --> 00:09:01.699
I'm just going to focus on a couple of quick
features here. So I'm just going to right-click

00:09:01.699 --> 00:09:08.699
and add attribute. And I'm going to add the
X-Webkit -- oops -- how about if I type properly

00:09:13.310 --> 00:09:17.689
-- speech attribute. And I can close the dev
tools.

00:09:17.689 --> 00:09:21.439
And so sort of as if by magic, there's -- a
little microphone appeared. Now, I haven't

00:09:21.439 --> 00:09:25.429
done anything else. I haven't added any event
handlers or written any code. I just added

00:09:25.429 --> 00:09:31.019
that one attribute to this application. It
wasn't originally designed with speech in

00:09:31.019 --> 00:09:38.019
mind. That's adding the attribute.
Let's give it a try and see if this works.

00:09:38.079 --> 00:09:42.929
Now, I should caveat that one of the first
rules of keynotes is never, ever do live speech

00:09:42.929 --> 00:09:49.660
demos. The acoustics in the room make it really
hard. But we're going to try anyway. And I

00:09:49.660 --> 00:09:53.300
figure if it goes absolutely horribly wrong,
it will at least be entertaining. So let's

00:09:53.300 --> 00:09:57.220
see what happens.
So one of my favorite shows right now is called

00:09:57.220 --> 00:10:02.769
bandwagon. It stars Emma Caufield from Buffy
and a host of other movies. I'm going to search

00:10:02.769 --> 00:10:09.769
for that and see what happens. Let's try this.
Emma Caufield.

00:10:09.769 --> 00:10:13.359
Oh, it works. My gosh. That's -- you have
no idea --

00:10:13.359 --> 00:10:18.189
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Ian Ellison-Taylor: -- how -- I am genuinely

00:10:18.189 --> 00:10:22.279
surprised.
I'm genuinely surprised that works. And here's

00:10:22.279 --> 00:10:27.399
Bandwagon, the show. And I can click through
and watch it very quickly.

00:10:27.399 --> 00:10:33.230
Let's close that.
So that's fantastic, it did well with my bizarre

00:10:33.230 --> 00:10:38.959
English, slash, American accent.
So as you can imagine, at Google, we're adding

00:10:38.959 --> 00:10:42.819
speech support to a lot of our applications
as well. What I want to show you quickly and

00:10:42.819 --> 00:10:46.929
one of my favorites is translate. This is
something -- I like showing this because I

00:10:46.929 --> 00:10:51.879
genuinely need this. I am terrible at foreign
languages. And so this is a great -- it's

00:10:51.879 --> 00:10:55.149
a great way to do quick translation. And you
can try this out.

00:10:55.149 --> 00:11:01.449
I'm going to do -- I'm going to do a translation
from English into Chinese. I think Chinese

00:11:01.449 --> 00:11:07.040
is the language I am least likely to learn
in the future. So this is a good test.

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:12.019
Like I said, this has already been modified,
so it has the little microphone icon down

00:11:12.019 --> 00:11:14.239
here.
Welcome to San Francisco.

00:11:14.239 --> 00:11:21.239
It works. Amazing.
All right. So it's -- it's taken the speech,

00:11:21.249 --> 00:11:27.329
translated to Chinese. We can listen to this
now. (Chinese).

00:11:27.329 --> 00:11:32.980
&gt;&gt;Ian Ellison-Taylor: One more time. (Chinese).
&gt;&gt;Ian Ellison-Taylor: So I don't actually

00:11:32.980 --> 00:11:38.179
speak Chinese. So I have no idea if that was
actually correct. Does anyone -- people are

00:11:38.179 --> 00:11:40.089
nodding. Yes, all right.
[ Applause ]

00:11:40.089 --> 00:11:45.370
&gt;&gt;Ian Ellison-Taylor: I was afraid there for
a second I was going to insult someone's mother.

00:11:45.370 --> 00:11:47.889
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Ian Ellison-Taylor: But I think we did okay.

00:11:47.889 --> 00:11:54.889
All right. So that's, just quickly, speech.
New features are fantastic, of course. But

00:11:55.600 --> 00:11:59.999
performance is a feature, too.
And making things fast has been one of the

00:11:59.999 --> 00:12:04.600
sort of fundamental founding criteria of Chrome
since the very early days.

00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:10.129
So you can see behind me, this is a little
chart of JavaScript performance. And back

00:12:10.129 --> 00:12:15.309
in -- this is back in 2008 -- and this is
the best of. This isn't just Chrome. This

00:12:15.309 --> 00:12:19.559
is what was the state of the art of JavaScript
back in the day. And if you look at what's

00:12:19.559 --> 00:12:26.559
happened since then up to Chrome 11, the progress
on JavaScript has been truly phenomenal. It's

00:12:27.459 --> 00:12:32.600
fundamentally changed the kinds of applications
you can build on the Web.

00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:38.999
And, you know, in some respects, I'm kind
of hoping I never share this chart again.

00:12:38.999 --> 00:12:42.720
We're going to continue to work on JavaScript
performance, of course. But the good news

00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:48.239
here is, really, it's no longer the bottleneck
that it used to be. And so we're beginning

00:12:48.239 --> 00:12:52.899
to focus more of our attention on some of
the areas -- other areas of the Web platform,

00:12:52.899 --> 00:12:56.939
where there are more opportunities to make
performance improvements.

00:12:56.939 --> 00:13:02.480
Now, one of those areas, one of the key areas
is, of course, graphics. And, specifically,

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:09.179
GPU acceleration, using the GPU to hardware-accelerate
graphics and get the best out of the performance

00:13:09.179 --> 00:13:14.179
of your modern laptop as well as improve battery
life.

00:13:14.179 --> 00:13:18.629
One of the easiest ways to do that is using
CSS transforms. I know many of you will have

00:13:18.629 --> 00:13:23.929
been using CSS for a while now. It's super
easy to do. And it's in beta right now in

00:13:23.929 --> 00:13:29.100
Chrome, where those are now GPU-accelerated.
So you don't have to do anything to your applications.

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:32.119
Just keep using CSS and things will just get
magically faster.

00:13:32.119 --> 00:13:38.670
CSS is great.
Now, a level up in terms of capability is

00:13:38.670 --> 00:13:45.519
Canvas 2D. Canvas 2D is particularly important,
because it's used for a lot of games. And

00:13:45.519 --> 00:13:51.239
in games, one of the most common operations
that you want to do and have be fast is sprite

00:13:51.239 --> 00:13:56.379
animation, moving lots of little images or
animated characters zipping around.

00:13:56.379 --> 00:13:59.779
So that's one of the areas that we've been
focusing on heavily in the latest releases

00:13:59.779 --> 00:14:03.509
of Chrome.
So I'm going to give you a quick demo of what

00:14:03.509 --> 00:14:08.529
that looks like in Chrome.
So for the purposes of the demo, I'm going

00:14:08.529 --> 00:14:15.529
to use the famous, some would say infamous,
fishy demo, courtesy of Microsoft.

00:14:16.829 --> 00:14:23.049
So this is Chrome, running in software. It
does pretty well with 20 fish. But if you

00:14:23.049 --> 00:14:29.579
go up to, say, like, 100 or let's go to 500,
you can see there the frame rate's dropping.

00:14:29.579 --> 00:14:36.579
We're under ten frames a second.
So here is a new version of Chrome with GPU

00:14:37.220 --> 00:14:43.689
acceleration turned on for the canvas. You
can see here at 100 frames a second, 100 fish,

00:14:43.689 --> 00:14:50.689
still doing 60 frames a second.
Go up to 250. Keep going. 500.

00:14:51.040 --> 00:14:57.410
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Ian Ellison-Taylor: Thank you, thank you.

00:14:57.410 --> 00:15:01.199
You can applause.
It's not until we get to 1,000 fish where

00:15:01.199 --> 00:15:08.199
you start to see it going below 60 frames
per second. So that's basically a 10x improvement

00:15:08.759 --> 00:15:12.579
over where we were. So I think that's phenomenal.
And again, you didn't have to do anything.

00:15:12.579 --> 00:15:18.739
Things just got faster. So definitely try
out Canvas 2D. I think that's phenomenal.

00:15:18.739 --> 00:15:22.790
But wait, there's more!
So doing this kind of sprite animation is

00:15:22.790 --> 00:15:27.350
actually something that WebGL is extremely
good at doing.

00:15:27.350 --> 00:15:34.350
So our friends at Mozilla actually took the
fishy demo and ported it over to use WebGL.

00:15:35.879 --> 00:15:39.939
So let's look at a thousand fish straight
away. Let's just jump to that.

00:15:39.939 --> 00:15:42.639
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Ian Ellison-Taylor: So that's too easy.

00:15:42.639 --> 00:15:47.499
2,000. Still too easy.
10,000. All right.

00:15:47.499 --> 00:15:53.339
So now we are up to 10,000 or so Sprites and
still doing around 30 frames per second.

00:15:53.339 --> 00:16:00.339
So this is another 10x performance improvement,
and it's very easy to move that kind of sprite

00:16:00.649 --> 00:16:04.879
animation over to WebGL.
It's a fantastic way to take advantage of

00:16:04.879 --> 00:16:11.879
the performance of a modern laptop. I think
this is pretty phenomenal.

00:16:12.059 --> 00:16:16.109
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Ian Ellison-Taylor: Yes, authentication.

00:16:16.109 --> 00:16:20.879
Applause, applause.
So do definitely give that a try.

00:16:20.879 --> 00:16:25.359
Now, WebGL can be used for lots of things.
It's not just good for sprite animation. It

00:16:25.359 --> 00:16:31.160
is full 3D. So just briefly, I wanted to show
an example of sort of a more traditional 3D

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:35.040
application.
So this is Tinkercad that lets you do a little

00:16:35.040 --> 00:16:42.040
bit of design on a surface here, and I am
just going to quickly draw some shapes. And

00:16:47.119 --> 00:16:48.509
I have to apologize for not being a designer,
and, you know, not having any artistic ability

00:16:48.509 --> 00:16:51.379
whatsoever. But I can build a little model
surface and I can quickly punch holes in the

00:16:51.379 --> 00:16:58.379
surface. Let's do that. So I can do some solid
geometry modeling. This is running in the

00:16:59.989 --> 00:17:03.579
browser, and I am zoom in and out. And the
performance of this is absolutely fantastic.

00:17:03.579 --> 00:17:07.689
I didn't have to install any plug-ins. This
is just using the inherent 3D support that's

00:17:07.689 --> 00:17:12.689
in the browser now.
So I think this is pretty cool. And Tinkercad

00:17:12.689 --> 00:17:18.189
in particular I think is fantastic. You should
try this out because it lets you export these

00:17:18.189 --> 00:17:23.149
3D models and send them to a 3D printer. So
you can actually build the things that you

00:17:23.149 --> 00:17:30.149
design, which I think is absolutely phenomenal.
So that's it for WebGL and some features.

00:17:31.389 --> 00:17:37.580
So those are great features, and of course
there's going to be lots more to come. There's

00:17:37.580 --> 00:17:43.480
hundreds of features coming in a build near
you. So stay tuned for upcoming releases.

00:17:43.480 --> 00:17:48.470
And with that, I thank you.
[ Applause ]

00:17:48.470 --> 00:17:55.470
&gt;&gt;Sundar Pichai: Thank you, Ian.
Speed is the fundamental underpinning behind

00:17:57.200 --> 00:18:00.899
Chrome, and I think these GP acceleration
improvements is going to make Chrome much

00:18:00.899 --> 00:18:04.409
faster.
In fact, for example, if you were writing

00:18:04.409 --> 00:18:08.970
a game about six months ago and you were writing
it in canvas and software, and if you can

00:18:08.970 --> 00:18:14.360
now write it in WebGL, GP accelerated, it's
going to be about 100 times faster. So that's

00:18:14.360 --> 00:18:19.080
the pace at which the Web is evolving.
Of course writing these applications only

00:18:19.080 --> 00:18:26.080
matter if you can reach users, which is why
about three months ago in the stable channel

00:18:26.110 --> 00:18:32.610
of the U.S. we launched the Chrome Web Store.
The goal behind the Web Store was to help

00:18:32.610 --> 00:18:36.690
developers reach users and monetize their
applications.

00:18:36.690 --> 00:18:42.399
In the first three months since we have launched,
we have had amazing early traction. We have

00:18:42.399 --> 00:18:48.970
had over 17 million applications installed,
and more importantly, developers have informed

00:18:48.970 --> 00:18:54.000
us that people spend a lot more time in their
application when they install it from the

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:58.269
Chrome Web Store.
To give you some examples, roughly we see

00:18:58.269 --> 00:19:03.649
about a 2x increase in the amount of time
spent per app when installed from the Web

00:19:03.649 --> 00:19:08.029
Store. Springpad, which is a productivity
application, has noticed this increase, and

00:19:08.029 --> 00:19:14.500
so have many others. And games. Games have
seen about two and a half times increase in

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:19.919
transactions when users have installed a game
in the Web Store.

00:19:19.919 --> 00:19:26.919
So we are taking the Web Store and as of today
we are making it available in 41 languages

00:19:27.100 --> 00:19:30.809
to all 160 million users of Chrome.
[ Applause ]

00:19:30.809 --> 00:19:37.809
&gt;&gt;Sundar Pichai: We are very excited that
you as developers can write an application

00:19:40.110 --> 00:19:44.509
and reach the entire install base of Chrome.
When you write these applications there are

00:19:44.509 --> 00:19:49.100
two aspects of it. The first is reach, so
we want to make sure you can reach all users

00:19:49.100 --> 00:19:53.980
of Chrome, but more importantly we want to
make sure you can monetize your applications.

00:19:53.980 --> 00:20:00.240
This is why when we launched Chrome Web Store
we offered the ability for you to charge for

00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:05.279
your applications. But we want to constantly
explore more options by which developers can

00:20:05.279 --> 00:20:11.750
monetize. One of the problems on the Web today,
it's very tough to charge users in context

00:20:11.750 --> 00:20:16.750
within your application without breaking the
flow. So we want to create a seamless payment

00:20:16.750 --> 00:20:22.429
experience for developers and users alike.
To talk about that, let me invite Vikas Gupta,

00:20:22.429 --> 00:20:28.220
product manager on the Google Payments Team.
[ Applause ]

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:35.220
&gt;&gt;Vikas Gupta: Thank you, Sundar. Hello, everyone.
I am tremendously excited to be here today

00:20:39.669 --> 00:20:45.480
to talk about in-app payments. In some ways,
it's the culmination of a vision that our

00:20:45.480 --> 00:20:50.529
team has been working on for the past few
years. It started with the basic idea that

00:20:50.529 --> 00:20:56.429
we can make purchases within applications
extremely frictionless, extremely seamless

00:20:56.429 --> 00:21:03.029
so users who are engaged in your applications
can stay engaged while they make a purchase.

00:21:03.029 --> 00:21:07.269
It should be really easy for developers to
implement it, and should be just as secure

00:21:07.269 --> 00:21:09.899
and reliable as every online purchase should
be.

00:21:09.899 --> 00:21:14.970
What's even more exciting for us today is
that we're delivering that vision at Google

00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:19.500
scale. That means you can take this and take
it to users everywhere on the Web.

00:21:19.500 --> 00:21:26.500
Let me show you a little bit of how it works.
This is an application built by Graphic.ly.

00:21:29.120 --> 00:21:35.059
It's available in the Web Store. It let's
you discover, browse, read and enjoy comic

00:21:35.059 --> 00:21:40.100
books and graphic novels on the Web. It's
a great, fun experience, and I highly encourage

00:21:40.100 --> 00:21:44.429
all of to you to go check it out.
