00:57:24.799 --> 00:57:31.799
&gt;&gt;Sundar Pichai: Be another group which suffers
from the same complexity in computing are

00:57:37.549 --> 00:57:43.319
businesses and educational institutions. Schools.
Let's take a brief look at what their world

00:57:43.319 --> 00:57:47.519
looks like.
In most companies today, the IP infrastructure

00:57:47.519 --> 00:57:52.990
is so complicated, they actually have a hard
time even accounting for the layers and layers

00:57:52.990 --> 00:57:58.430
of software they have within their companies.
In fact, it is so difficult to upgrade operating

00:57:58.430 --> 00:58:02.890
systems, over 50% of the companies are still
running Windows XP.

00:58:02.890 --> 00:58:09.890
This morning I checked in Wikipedia, Windows
XP was launched in 2001, ten years ago, so

00:58:10.190 --> 00:58:15.420
most companies have such a hard time upgrading
their operating systems. It is very, very

00:58:15.420 --> 00:58:19.950
costly to do so.
Meanwhile, usage patterns have changed dramatically.

00:58:19.950 --> 00:58:25.529
Ten years ago, people used to use desktops.
Today, most users use laptops. They take it

00:58:25.529 --> 00:58:30.809
in and out of the enterprise firewall. They're
always connected. The security surface area

00:58:30.809 --> 00:58:34.809
is really challenging for I.T. administrators
to manage.

00:58:34.809 --> 00:58:40.740
All this adds up as costs for companies. If
you just do a rough survey, most companies

00:58:40.740 --> 00:58:47.740
spend starting from 3,000 to high thousands
of dollars per computer per year when they

00:58:48.160 --> 00:58:55.160
deploy a PC environment. So it's really complicated.
There is good news. CIOs and I.T. administrators

00:58:56.089 --> 00:59:01.099
are well on their way to move things towards
the cloud. Cloud computing is real and big

00:59:01.099 --> 00:59:04.779
in the enterprise.
So if you look at it, even many traditional

00:59:04.779 --> 00:59:11.510
applications are already moving to the cloud.
Companies like SAP, SalesForce.com, are pioneering

00:59:11.510 --> 00:59:16.690
this movement, so you can now, within companies,
use all of them as Web applications.

00:59:16.690 --> 00:59:22.019
In addition, many companies are deploying
desktop virtualization. So they are taking

00:59:22.019 --> 00:59:27.269
the visual applications and bringing them
through a browser front end to their users.

00:59:27.269 --> 00:59:31.809
So for Chromebooks, we have partnered with
two of the leading retailers in the space,

00:59:31.809 --> 00:59:38.809
Citrix and VMware, to make sure the same applications
are available in Chromebooks through the browser.

00:59:40.059 --> 00:59:47.059
When we launched the Cr-48 pilot program,
we had over 50,000 companies apply to test

00:59:47.130 --> 00:59:53.510
Chromebooks. We have deployed them in hundreds
of companies and thousands of devices.

00:59:53.510 --> 00:59:58.730
Here are a few examples.
Intercontinental Hotels. They have hundreds

00:59:58.730 --> 01:00:04.849
of call service agents in distributed locations.
They have been piloting Chromebooks to great

01:00:04.849 --> 01:00:08.690
results.
A more classic example is Jason's Deli. They

01:00:08.690 --> 01:00:14.380
have hundreds of retail store locations all
over the U.S. It is so cost-prohibitive for

01:00:14.380 --> 01:00:20.390
them that in many stores, all store managers
share one Windows laptop in the back of the

01:00:20.390 --> 01:00:24.150
store.
So we took a few stores, deployed Chromebooks.

01:00:24.150 --> 01:00:28.970
Every store manager gets one. They've been
able to seamlessly manage the deployment.

01:00:28.970 --> 01:00:35.789
We have tested this with governmental institutions.
The city of Orlando, if you go there, you

01:00:35.789 --> 01:00:42.369
will find Chromebooks in offices, in some
cases inside fire trucks, and in some cases,

01:00:42.369 --> 01:00:45.349
even on the streets.
In fact, the only piece of feedback they've

01:00:45.349 --> 01:00:49.500
had is people have asked for more power cards,
because they are using them everywhere. So

01:00:49.500 --> 01:00:55.619
this is really, really easy to use.
We did -- we spent four months talking to

01:00:55.619 --> 01:01:01.619
over 400 companies and had an in-depth survey
of where the Chromebooks are applicable. Almost

01:01:01.619 --> 01:01:07.329
all companies said that the combination of
Web applications and desktop virtualization,

01:01:07.329 --> 01:01:12.650
they can migrate 75% of their users today
to Chromebooks.

01:01:12.650 --> 01:01:19.019
So we want to make it available to them, the
same two Chromebooks which are available for

01:01:19.019 --> 01:01:23.380
consumers will be available for businesses
as well.

01:01:23.380 --> 01:01:29.599
In addition, when we talked with them, not
everyone has a mobile use case. For example,

01:01:29.599 --> 01:01:34.960
in retail store locations, they want a box
from which they can drive large monitors.

01:01:34.960 --> 01:01:38.510
Google engineers wanted the same thing as
well. They wanted a box from which they can

01:01:38.510 --> 01:01:43.480
drive large monitors. We are working on a
Chromebooks as well which we think will be

01:01:43.480 --> 01:01:48.880
ideal for many, many companies.
So how will we offer this?

01:01:48.880 --> 01:01:53.420
As I said earlier, the device is only one
part of the cost.

01:01:53.420 --> 01:01:59.440
Most of the expenses are in management and
administration. So we worked to design a Web

01:01:59.440 --> 01:02:06.180
console so just from a Web page, I.T. administrators
can centrally manage all Chromebooks. They

01:02:06.180 --> 01:02:12.309
can add and remove users. They can install
apps, remove applications, have centralized

01:02:12.309 --> 01:02:18.319
group policy settings for their entire employee
base. It's dead simple to manage.

01:02:18.319 --> 01:02:25.019
We want to make it really easy for them to
manage their computing, so we have an end-to-end

01:02:25.019 --> 01:02:31.839
offering. We call this Chromebooks for Business.
For the first time, it is software and hardware

01:02:31.839 --> 01:02:36.490
as a service, packaged together.
So what do companies get? They get the devices,

01:02:36.490 --> 01:02:43.490
they get Chromebooks. You get a centralized
Web console. You get full support. You get

01:02:43.670 --> 01:02:49.539
warranty and replacements. So if your device
breaks down, we ship you a new device. And

01:02:49.539 --> 01:02:56.539
when the hardware life cycle is over, we automatically
upgrade you to the next generation Chromebook.

01:02:56.619 --> 01:03:00.599
All for a convenient monthly price of $28
per user.

01:03:00.599 --> 01:03:05.839
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Sundar Pichai: Software and hardware as

01:03:05.839 --> 01:03:09.589
a service.
[ Cheers and applause ]

01:03:09.589 --> 01:03:15.339
&gt;&gt;Sundar Pichai: We think this can fundamentally
change the way people use computing in companies.

01:03:15.339 --> 01:03:22.339
Another area which we passionately care about
is schools. It's incredible that in today's

01:03:22.750 --> 01:03:27.240
age, most schools can't provide computers
for their students. Again, the reasons are

01:03:27.240 --> 01:03:32.059
the same. You can go and buy a cheap PC, but
it's impossible -- we have talked to every

01:03:32.059 --> 01:03:38.200
school -- it's impossible to manage a deployment
of a thousand PCs in a cost-effective manner.

01:03:38.200 --> 01:03:42.309
They just cannot afford it.
So we want to make it possible for every student

01:03:42.309 --> 01:03:47.960
to have a computer in schools as well.
So we worked with our partners, and Chromebooks

01:03:47.960 --> 01:03:54.960
for Education is priced at $20 per user for
schools and governmental institutions.

